Protecting Internal Traffic with TLS
Objectives
Configure and use automatic service certificates.

1. What is TLS?
TLS = Transport Layer Security
Purpose:
Encrypt communication
Verify server identity
Protect data integrity
Without TLS:
Client → Server
DATA = Plain text
Anyone can read it.
With TLS:
Client → Server
DATA = Encrypted
Attackers cannot read or modify traffic.
________________________________________
2. Zero-Trust Security Model
A Zero-Trust environment assumes:
Nothing is trusted automatically
Every connection must verify:
Identity
Authorization
Encryption
Principles:
1️⃣ Always verify identity
2️⃣ Encrypt communication
3️⃣ Allow only explicit access
Example:
Frontend → Backend
Frontend must verify:
Backend certificate
________________________________________
3. Default OpenShift Network Security
OpenShift already encrypts cluster management traffic.
Example:
Node ↔ Control Plane
Traffic encrypted automatically.
This is stronger than default Kubernetes.
________________________________________
But application traffic is NOT encrypted by default.
Example:
Pod A → Pod B
Traffic is:
HTTP (unencrypted)
For zero-trust environments we must add:
TLS encryption
________________________________________
4. Two Types of TLS in OpenShift
OpenShift secures traffic in two main areas.
1️⃣ External Traffic
From outside the cluster.
Example:
Internet → OpenShift Application
Secured using:
Routes + TLS
________________________________________
2️⃣ Internal Traffic
Between applications inside cluster.
Example:
Pod A → Pod B
Secured using:
Service Certificates
________________________________________
5. Securing External Traffic with Routes
Routes expose applications.
Example route:
www.example.com
External client accesses:
https://www.example.com
Routes support three TLS types.
________________________________________
6. TLS Termination Types
1️⃣ Edge Termination
TLS ends at router.
Client (HTTPS)
     │
     ▼
Router (decrypt)
     │
     ▼
Pod (HTTP)
Traffic inside cluster:
NOT encrypted
Pros:
Simple
Cons:
Not secure internally
________________________________________
2️⃣ Passthrough Termination
Router does not decrypt TLS.
Client (HTTPS)
     │
     ▼
Router
     │
     ▼
Pod (HTTPS)
Pod handles TLS.
Pros:
End-to-end encryption
Cons:
Router cannot inspect traffic
________________________________________
3️⃣ Re-encrypt Termination
Most secure route type.
Client (HTTPS)
     │
     ▼
Router (decrypt)
     │
     ▼
Router (re-encrypt)
     │
     ▼
Pod (HTTPS)
Traffic always encrypted.
Requires certificate on pod.
________________________________________
7. Creating Secure Routes
Example command:
oc create route edge myroute \
--service=myservice \
--hostname=app.example.com
For passthrough:
oc create route passthrough myroute \
--service=myservice
________________________________________
8. Securing Internal Traffic
OpenShift uses a component called:
service-ca controller
Purpose:
Automatically generate TLS certificates
for services.
________________________________________
9. How Service Certificates Work
Step-by-step process:
1 Create service
2 Add annotation
3 OpenShift generates certificate
4 Certificate stored in secret
5 Pod mounts secret
6 Application uses TLS
________________________________________
10. Generating Service Certificates
Add annotation to service.
Command:
oc annotate service hello \
service.beta.openshift.io/serving-cert-secret-name=hello-secret
Explanation:
Part	Meaning
service hello	service name
serving-cert-secret-name	secret name
hello-secret	generated TLS secret
________________________________________
11. What Happens After Annotation
OpenShift automatically creates:
Secret: hello-secret
Contents:
tls.crt
tls.key
These files contain:
Certificate
Private key
Check secret:
oc get secret hello-secret
________________________________________
12. Using the Certificate in a Pod
Application must mount the secret.
Example Deployment YAML patch
spec:
  template:
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: hello
        volumeMounts:
        - name: hello-volume
          mountPath: /etc/pki/nginx/
Meaning:
Mount TLS files into container
________________________________________
Volume Definition
volumes:
- name: hello-volume
  secret:
    secretName: hello-secret
Meaning:
Mount secret as volume
________________________________________
TLS File Mapping
items:
- key: tls.crt
  path: server.crt
Meaning:
Certificate location
________________________________________
- key: tls.key
  path: private/server.key
Meaning:
Private key location
Application now serves HTTPS.
________________________________________
13. Client Application Verification
Clients must verify certificates.
For that they need:
CA certificate
CA = Certificate Authority
________________________________________
14. Injecting the CA Bundle
OpenShift can inject the CA automatically.
Create configmap:
oc create configmap ca-bundle
________________________________________
Add annotation:
oc annotate configmap ca-bundle \
service.beta.openshift.io/inject-cabundle=true
Now OpenShift inserts CA certificate into:
data.service-ca.crt
Check configmap:
oc get configmap ca-bundle -o yaml
________________________________________
15. Mount CA Bundle in Client Pod
Mount configmap as volume.
Example:
Client Pod
   │
   ▼
Reads CA certificate
   │
   ▼
Validates server certificate
Ensures:
Server is trusted
________________________________________
16. Important Warning
The service-ca controller replaces all data in the configmap.
Therefore:
Use a dedicated configmap
Do not mix with other configuration.
________________________________________
17. Certificate Rotation
Certificates expire.
OpenShift automatically rotates them.
Service CA validity:
26 months
Rotation happens when:
Remaining validity < 13 months
________________________________________
18. Grace Period
During rotation:
Old certificate still valid
for:
13 months
However:
Pods must restart
to load the new certificate.
________________________________________
19. Manual Certificate Rotation
You can rotate service certificate manually.
Delete secret:
oc delete secret hello-secret
Result:
service-ca controller regenerates it
________________________________________
20. Rotating the CA Certificate
Command:
oc delete secret/signing-key \
-n openshift-service-ca
Effect:
New CA certificate created
⚠ Warning:
All pods must restart
Otherwise TLS fails.
________________________________________
21. Alternatives for TLS
OpenShift also supports advanced tools.
________________________________________
1️⃣ Service Mesh
Technology:
Istio-based
Provides:
mTLS (mutual TLS)
Traffic management
Observability
________________________________________
2️⃣ cert-manager
Operator that:
automates certificates
Example:
Let's Encrypt integration
Handles:
certificate creation
renewal
expiration
________________________________________
22. Security Architecture Example
Example secure architecture:
Internet
   │
HTTPS
   ▼
Router
   │
Re-encrypted TLS
   ▼
Frontend Pod
   │
TLS
   ▼
Backend Pod
   │
TLS
   ▼
Database
All communication encrypted.
